	biburl = {https://dblp.org/rec/conf/esorics/BhudiaOH24.bib},
	bibsource = {dblp computer science bibliography, https://dblp.org},
	abstract = {Recent research has shown the viability of ransomware attacks on Ethereum Proof-of-Stake (PoS) validators, whereby an attacker that compromises\xa0a validator can threaten to perform slashable actions unless a ransom is paid. Given the size of Ethereum validator stakes, validators could become\xa0an attractive target for future ransomware. However, there are currently\xa0no practical mechanisms to recover from ransomware since even validators\xa0that attempt to exit the network are retrospectively slashable during\xa0the withdrawal period. We propose  Revoke, an extension of Ethereum that mitigates\xa0the impact of ransomware attacks on validators.  Revoke  introduces\xa0a new decentralised key revocation mechanism that enables validators to change\xa0their signing key without withdrawing their stake. A challenge\xa0for  Revoke  is balancing the utility of the revocation mechanism\xa0for individual validators against potential reductions in overall chain security.  Revoke  exposes a trade-off whereby validators cannot propose or attest to blocks during the revocation process, and hence incur inactivity penalties, but are\xa0not susceptible to much larger slashing penalties. Our design extends\xa0the Ethereum specification to capture the impact of  Revoke ’s core key-change mechanism on both the beacon-chain state transition function and fork-choice decisions. We also adapt the existing safety and liveness proofs of Ethereum\xa0to incorporate the effects of  Revoke.}
}


